What’s the Point? The Missing Piece of Criminal Justice Reform through Consensus and Compromise

I. Introduction Criminal justice reform has had a ﬁrm place in news headlines for more than a decade. When the mass incarceration crisis came to the fore in 2008, with reports that one in a hundred adults in America was behind bars, there had already long been cries for reducing the prison and jail populations.1 Reform has mainly been sought through two approaches: consensus through ballot initiative or legislative compromise. But these modes of reform share a fundamental failure: both often lack a clear articulation of the purpose of criminal sentencing. In other words, “What’s the point?” Without an agreement on the underlying purpose of criminal punishment, neither method of pursuing changes in the criminal justice system can ever produce meaningful, long-standing reform.
II. Compromise Our usual way of understanding criminal justice reform is through legislative compromise. For instance, the move from the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 to the Fair Sentencing Act of 2010 was the result of this slow legislative mechanism.2 The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986 was the long-standing, bipartisan criminal justice legislation that instituted what we know today as punitive mandatory minimum sentences for drug offenders, including the infamous 100:1 sentencing ratio for crack versus powder cocaine.3 Under that scheme, it took one hundred times more powder cocaine than crack cocaine to trigger the same mandatory minimum sentence.4 Despite many cries of protest against the racial and social injustice perpetuated by this harsh sentencing model, it took over twenty years for Congress to begin to seriously consider changes to the cocaine sentencing scheme.
As a step toward making those changes, the House Judiciary Committee’s Subcommittee on Crime, Terrorism, and Homeland Security held a hearing on May 21, 2009.5 The resulting House Report stated: “African Americans serve almost as much time in Federal prison for a drug offense (58.7 months) as whites do for a violent offense (61.7 months), largely due to sentencing laws such as the 100-to-1 crack-powder cocaine disparity.”6 A few months later, on October 15, 2009, Senator Richard Durbin, a Democrat from Illinois, introduced his version of the Fair Sentencing Act to “eliminate the sentencing disparity that exists in the United States between crack cocaine and

powder cocaine.”7 As Senator Durbin explained, the purpose was to accomplish “two very important goals: One goal is to restore fairness to drug sentencing and [the second is] to focus our limited Federal resources on the most effective way to end violent drug trafﬁcking.”8 On the issue of fairness, Durbin made an important observation about the disconnect between actual drug “crimes” and the punishment of those offenses.9 He stated, “It is important to note that the crack/powder disparity disproportionately affects African Americans. While African Americans constitute less than 30 percent of crack users, they make up 82 percent of those convicted of Federal crack offenses.”10 At the time, Durbin envisioned a 1:1 ratio for crack and powder cocaine sentencing. What followed instead was, as Durbin described it, “a good bipartisan compromise” that reduced the 100:1 ratio but did not completely eliminate the sentencing disparity.11
The resulting Fair Sentencing Act of 2010 decreased the powder-to-crack sentencing ratio to nearly 18:1.12 The mandatory minimum for a ﬁrst-time offense of simple possession was eliminated, and ﬁrst-time simple possession of any quantity of crack cocaine, like powder cocaine, will result in a sentence of no longer than one year.13 This legislative action had been a long time coming, but the slow march forward was not due to an effort to study the effects of drug sentencing or to any work toward agreement about what purpose Congress was actually trying to fulﬁll through drug sentencing. The legislative record gives no indication of a reasoned or reﬂective exercise that led legislators to settle upon an 18:1 ratio. Instead, it was simply the result of compromise.
In introducing the FSA, Senator Durbin explained that the bill had support “across the political spectrum” of groups, including police forces, the American Bar Association, the Leadership Conference of Civil Rights, and the United Methodist Church.14 However, though his bill calling for a 1:1 ratio for crack and powder cocaine sentencing passed in the Senate, it soon met challengers.15 Democratic and Republican members of the Senate Judiciary Committee quibbled over its details, resulting in the change to the 18:1 ratio.16 The bill met resistance in the House as well. Some, like Republican Representative Lamar Smith of Texas, opposed any reduction of drug offense penalties.17 As Representative Smith characterized it: “Now Congress is considering legislation to wind down the ﬁght against drug

