The history of the “reform” that led to the Fair Sentencing Act leaves us with the question “What’s the point?” There is no statement in the legislative record explaining that 18:1 better reaches punishment goals of retribution, deterrence, rehabilitation, or incapacitation than some other ratio. There is no report accompanying the 18:1 ratio in Senate Bill 1789. The most elucidating piece of legislative history on the 18:1 ratio is a letter dated July 10, 2010, from the Senate Judiciary Committee, which states:
The Fair Sentencing Act would establish an 18:1 crack-powder ratio, which reﬂects a bipartisan compromise that was reached in the Senate Judiciary Committee. This 18:1 ratio responds to concerns raised by many in law enforcement, who agree that the 100:1 disparity is unjustiﬁed, but argue that crack is associated with greater levels of violence and therefore should be subject to tougher penalties.24
It is safe to conclude that 18:1 was selected because it was acceptable to those who objected to a 1:1 ratio and could be praised as progress by those who were against the 100:1 ratio.25 That’s compromise. The shortcoming of compromise is that it muddles purpose because it is, by design, a give-and-take process: both sides try to get a little of what they want, knowing that they can never get all of it, because the two sides do not fully agree on the point of the changes in the ﬁrst place. Therefore, though “reform” legislation was eventually enacted, that legislation did not fundamentally change anything about the main characteristics of American criminal punishment—over-incarceration and extreme racial disparities.
The same failure to truly reform the sentencing landscape can be seen in the most recent federal criminal justice reform measure, the First Step Act of 2018.26 Signed into law in December 2019, it has been touted as the legislation that will bring the most signiﬁcant changes to the criminal

justice system in a generation.27 The Act does a number of things, including
• increasing good time credit from forty-seven days per year to ﬁfty-four;
• requiring the Bureau of Prisons to examine its capabilities in creating evidence-based recidivism reduction programs; and
• allowing participation in those programs to lead to incentives such as prerelease custody in a halfway house, increased visitation opportunities, email access, commissary funds, etc.28
While it may seem as though these provisions are in line with the wave of “smart on crime” reforms29 that focus on ways to reduce the prison population without increasing crime, the First Step Act has not been without criticism. Initially, several civil rights organizations opposed the Act. The Leadership Conference on Civil and Human Rights sent a letter to Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell and Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer asserting: “Without changes to sentencing laws that eliminate mandatory minimums, restore judicial discretion, reduce the national prison population, and mitigate disparate impacts on communities of color, the First Step Act alone will have little impact.”30 On the other side of the aisle, there were calls for remaining tough on crime while still appealing to an evangelical audience that believes in second chances.31 And so we are back to the same disappointment often delivered by compromise—a result that fails to radically transform the realities of mass incarceration. This outcome is to be expected because transformation is not the true goal of compromise. In fact, sentencing reform through compromise is rarely focused on achieving any speciﬁc purpose of punishment. Rather, its objective is to satisfy enough legislators to achieve a successful vote.
The limitations of reform through compromise are evident when we take a closer look at how the First Step Act will actually operate. The Act clariﬁes the deﬁnitions of serious drug felony and serious violent felony, and lowers the mandatory minimum sentences that apply to those classes of offenders from twenty years to ﬁfteen years— and, in the case of certain repeat drug offenders, from a mandatory life sentence to a mandatory minimum twenty-ﬁve-year sentence.32 These are certainly not insigniﬁcant changes. However, it remains unclear what the lower mandatory minimums truly accomplish. Time has shown that mandatory minimums do not lower the rates of crime, nor do they increase the rehabilitation of offenders.33 And, though Title I of the First Step Act declares that its goal is “recidivism reduction,” which would indicate a focus on deterrence and/or rehabilitation, several questions remain about how the proscribed risk assessment tools will actually operate.34 Further, we know that many offenders will not beneﬁt from the programs and incentives because their criminal histories will bar them from those opportunities.35 Those offenders will remain subject to the

