One of the seemingly most meaningful sentencing changes made by the First Step Act is that it renders the 18:1 ratio of the Fair Sentencing Act retroactively applicable to drug offenders sentenced before the Fair Sentencing Act was enacted.36 While this is another important change, it is equally important to note that the retroactive application is only triggered upon a motion and that its applicability is within the discretion of the sentencing judge.37 And so, some familiar questions bubble to the surface again. When will retroactivity apply to any given case? Why? How will this approach address racial and socioeconomic disparities in sentencing outcomes? Overall, this aspect of the First Step Act does little to clarify how any particular purpose of sentencing will actually be achieved.
Ultimately, the First Step Act does not reﬂect any fundamental change to our overall thinking about the use of incarceration or its consequences. It simply is not sweeping sentencing reform. Without changes to sentencing laws that (1) eliminate or greatly reduce mandatory minimums, (2) inform the use of judicial discretion, (3) intentionally develop strategies to reduce the national prison population, and (4) mitigate disparate impacts on communities of color and the economically disadvantaged, the First Step Act will have a very limited impact on mass incarceration. Without being clearly guided by a singular purpose, reform through legislative compromise can always only go so far. Steps rather than leaps may be all we can really expect. And it may take another decade for there to be any compromise that leads us to our next step.
III. Consensus Consensus is deﬁned as a general agreement.38 Across the country, we have seen efforts at consensus reform through ballot initiative—from the passing of recreational marijuana laws in places like Michigan to the attempt to pass sweeping drug sentencing reform through Ohio’s Ballot Issue 1.39 Issue 1 sought a constitutional amendment to change drug possession felonies to misdemeanors, prohibit prison sentences for technical violations, allow for sentence reductions through rehabilitative programs, and redirect the ﬁscal savings from reduced incarceration to drug treatment and victim services.40 This consensus movement indicates people’s fatigue with waiting for the slow churn of legislative compromise reform. Rather than wait, voters are put to the task of showing whether there is a general agreement, or consensus, about moving the law in a speciﬁc direction. And while these ballot initiatives have sometimes worked in the marijuana context, Ohio’s Issue 1 was soundly defeated by a vote of 63.4% to 36.6%.41 The failure of Ohio’s Issue 1 highlights that sweeping reform through consensus can suffer from the same weakness of reform through compromise—agreement on the need for reform does not show agreement on the purpose of reform. This lack of true, deep consensus can ultimately defeat efforts at large-scale reform through consensus.

One exciting aspect of Ohio Issue 1 was that, if it had passed, it would have told us clearly that the voters believe rehabilitation should be the purpose of drug possession sentencing. Rehabilitation is a theory of punishment that focuses on using punishment in order to transform the offender into a healthier, law-abiding person. The type of rehabilitative punishment called for by Issue 1 was focused and substantive. It was focused rehabilitation because it applied to speciﬁc categories of offenses: low-level, nonviolent drug possession and noncriminal probation violations. It clearly exempted offenders serving sentences of death or life imprisonment for murder, rape, or child molestation.42 Issue 1 was substantive in that it spelled out just how rehabilitative punishment was supposed to be carried out. If this initiative had passed in November 2019, sentencing credits would have been given to offenders who satisﬁed rehabilitation programs, making the punishment length directly related to how much “better” the offender is becoming.43 When it comes to rehabilitation, the punishment itself is supposed to change the offender for the better. Accordingly, Issue 1 was proposing an incentive for the offender to use the punishment experience in that manner. Perhaps most importantly, the proposed amendment was substantive in the sense that it provided guidance on how the rehabilitation programs should be funded.44 Though Issue 1 identiﬁed rehabilitation as the purpose of drug sentencing, the initiative also implied a few notable messages about the other purposes of punishment. By providing that drug possession offenses shall be classiﬁed no higher than a misdemeanor, the proposed constitutional amendment was making a statement about retribution. While retribution punishes someone for being morally blameworthy, it punishes them only to the extent of their blameworthiness. In other words, proportionality is essential to the theory of retribution. If Issue 1 had passed, it would have been clear that Ohio voters believed that felony punishment and resulting felony lengths of incarceration are disproportionate to the harm caused by the crime of drug possession. The drug possessor is not blameworthy enough to require incarceration. Likewise, the simple drug possessor is not dangerous enough to require lengthy incarceration, and thus an incapacitation theory is satisﬁed by misdemeanor-level punishment alone. Further, Issue 1 would have prohibited imprisoning a person on probation for noncriminal probation violations. This could be understood to represent a belief that incarceration does not deter these sorts of violations for drug possessors. These were uncompromised statements of purpose. However, Issue 1 did not pass. It is doubtful that its failure was due to a disagreement on the need for change. It is more likely that the measure failed because there is no general agreement on what we are trying to do when we punish people. And, without that agreement, a constitutional amendment enshrining these statements on purpose is difﬁcult to swallow.
This difﬁculty of reforming without agreeing on purpose is evident in the arguments made by opponents of

