Issue 1. Some argued that putting anything other than basic constitutional rights in a constitutional amendment is misguided.45 Others argued that Issue 1 was a one-sided proposal that would weaken the tools available to elected representatives, county prosecutors, and judges for making and enforcing laws.46 Arguably, it would have eliminated important incentives to encourage drug treatment for the addicted and allowed the drug dealers who prey on addiction to freely roam the streets. As it stands, drug courts use the threat of criminal punishment—and prison in particular—to get drug offenders to agree to addiction treatment. Therefore, if that threat were removed, some felt that judges would be less able to push people into treatment. In these particular opponents’ views, incarceration should be used as a device to curb recidivism. Supporters of Issue 1, however, viewed the purpose of criminal punishment differently.
When it comes to criminal justice reform, there is no question that we are in a moment of momentum. It is no longer controversial to recognize that a system of unbridled mass incarceration is undesirable for a host of reasons. However, despite the popularity of talking about criminal justice reform, it has not yet become popular to identify what we are actually trying to accomplish through criminal punishment and tailor reform efforts to that purpose. As discussed above, legislative compromise does not even attempt to identify these goals. And, as recent ballot efforts have shown, sweeping reform through consensus often requires consensus on purpose in order to succeed at the ballot. Without an effort to come to some agreement on the point of punishment, truly transformational criminal justice reform will continue to be stymied, regardless of the reform vehicle chosen. Reaching a consensus on the point of our criminal justice system—which would require confronting the true reasons why we incarcerate—may just be the missing piece that will allow us to begin to dismantle our overreliance on incarceration and prevent all the consequences of that addiction.
